In Week 5 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that had been forming snapped into clearer view. The presidency was no longer only pushing against the edges of law and custom; it was beginning to redraw the map of the state itself. The week\'92s events showed a government being hollowed out and rewired so that power flowed through a smaller circle of people and institutions, many of them private, many of them personally loyal. What changed was not just policy, but who could make policy, who could resist it, and what the public was allowed to see and remember. It was a week in which the machinery of a large democracy was treated as something to be stripped for parts. That was the point.\
\
At the start of Week 5, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:40 p.m. By the end, it read 7:43 p.m., a forward move of just over three minutes. The number is small, but the shift it marks is not. The clock moved because several traits that define democratic risk all worsened at once: law used as a weapon rather than a limit, civil service turned into a political spoil, state power outsourced to private actors, and the very idea of term limits pulled into open question. Courts still blocked some of the most extreme moves, and some state and foreign actors pushed back, but the balance of the week ran the other way. The executive branch, often through Elon Musk\'92s Department of Government Efficiency, gained new leverage over people, data, and institutions that had once been buffered from direct presidential will. The center of gravity moved.\
\
The most visible change came in the structure of the federal workforce. Through a web of executive orders and administrative actions, the administration moved from rhetoric about \'93draining the swamp\'94 to a coordinated purge. Mass firings swept through agencies that touch almost every aspect of public life: the CDC and HHS lost thousands of staff, including the entire first-year class of Epidemic Intelligence Service officers; the Forest Service and National Park Service prepared to terminate thousands more; the FAA dismissed hundreds responsible for air traffic control systems; USAID was allowed to furlough over 2,000 workers; and the IRS began layoffs of thousands of employees. Many of those targeted were still in probationary status, which made them easier to remove. The effect was not marginal. It was structural. Agencies that manage pandemics, wildfires, nuclear security, foreign aid, and land stewardship were left with fewer hands and less memory. The justification was efficiency and cost-cutting. The result was a state less able to act independently of the president and his chosen lieutenants.\
\
These firings did not happen in isolation. They were the operational arm of a new architecture centered on DOGE, the Department of Government Efficiency, led in practice by Elon Musk. An earlier executive order had empowered DOGE to oversee workforce \'93optimization,\'94 and in Week 5 that authority was exercised across the system. DOGE representatives gained access to sensitive systems at health agencies and pressed for entry into IRS and Social Security databases. The acting head of the Social Security Administration, Michelle King, chose retirement rather than hand over beneficiary data; staff at the General Services Administration resigned rather than grant a Musk ally access to Notify.gov, a system that can send messages to the public. These resignations were acts of conscience, but they also cleared the way for replacements more willing to comply. The civil service, designed to be neutral and durable, was being reshaped into a workforce that understood its survival as contingent on political obedience. That was the lesson.\
