Courts were asked to stand in the way of this restructuring and, in crucial moments, declined. A federal judge refused to block DOGE\'92s access to Education Department data systems. Another declined to issue a temporary restraining order against mass firings, allowing layoffs at the IRS and other agencies to proceed. A separate ruling permitted USAID to place thousands of workers on leave. These decisions did not endorse every aspect of the administration\'92s agenda, but they did something almost as consequential: they treated sweeping personnel changes and data grabs as within the normal range of executive discretion. At the same time, a court approved an eight-month severance offer to encourage voluntary resignations across the federal workforce, turning the buyout into a judicially blessed tool for thinning the ranks. In each case, the law did not simply fail to protect the civil service; it actively smoothed the path for its transformation. The guardrails held in form, but not in effect.\
\
Alongside these structural moves came a set of orders that pulled independent regulators closer to the White House. One executive order required most independent agencies to submit their rules to the Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs for review, giving the president\'92s staff a gatekeeping role over what had been semi-autonomous bodies. Another order, issued under the banner of a DOGE \'93deregulatory initiative,\'94 instructed agencies to identify and de-prioritize regulations the administration deemed unconstitutional or beyond statutory authority. A third order gave the White House a say over the budgets and policy priorities of agencies like the SEC and FTC. These steps did not abolish the agencies, but they changed who they answered to. Instead of balancing congressional mandates, expert judgment, and public comment, they were told to align with the president\'92s view of the Constitution and the market. The effect was to make the executive branch both author and judge of its own regulatory reach. Oversight turned inward.\
\
The justice system itself was pulled deeper into this orbit. The week saw the culmination of a crisis around the corruption case against New York City Mayor Eric Adams. DOJ leadership confined Public Integrity Section lawyers to a room and gave them an hour to decide who would sign a dismissal or be fired. At least five lawyers resigned rather than comply. The acting U.S. attorney for the Southern District of New York, Danielle Sassoon, also stepped down, as did the Criminal Division Chief in Washington, Denise Cheung, who refused to open a legally baseless probe into a Biden-era contract. Despite these resignations, the department moved ahead: the bribery case against Adams was dropped, and a judge in Manhattan pressed DOJ officials on why policy considerations, rather than the merits, were driving the decision. The answer, in practice, was clear. Prosecutorial discretion was being used to trade away accountability in exchange for cooperation on immigration enforcement, including federal operations on Rikers Island. Law, in this setting, was not a limit on power but a currency. It could be spent.\
