At the same time, the administration moved to secure loyal leadership at the top of federal law enforcement. Kash Patel, a close Trump ally known for his willingness to name supposed \'93deep state\'94 enemies, was confirmed by a single vote as FBI director and sworn in on February 21. Almost immediately, he began relocating up to 1,500 agents away from headquarters, in line with his stated desire to refocus the bureau on left-wing protest groups while downplaying far-right threats. In Washington, Ed Martin, a Stop the Steal activist and lawyer for January 6 defendants, was nominated as U.S. attorney and continued to serve in that role on an interim basis. He launched \'93Operation Whirlwind,\'94 an initiative ostensibly aimed at threats against officials, but one that quickly sent letters to Senator Chuck Schumer and Representative Robert Garcia asking them to explain critical remarks about Elon Musk. The message to prosecutors and agents was simple. Loyalty to the president and his allies would be rewarded with power. Resistance would be met with pressure or removal.\
