The same pattern appeared in how the administration treated those who had attacked the democratic process itself. On his first day back in office, Trump pardoned more than 1,500 people involved in the January 6 assault on the Capitol. In Week 5, some of these individuals were celebrated at CPAC as heroes, even as conference organizers quietly ejected others. Enrique Tarrio, the former Proud Boys leader whose 22-year sentence for seditious conspiracy had been wiped away, was arrested again near the Capitol for allegedly assaulting a protester. The clemency and the celebration told one story; the new arrest told another. Together they showed how the line between political violence and ordinary politics had blurred. Those who had once stormed the seat of legislative power now moved in and out of mainstream conservative spaces, shielded at the top and policed only when their actions became impossible to ignore. Impunity had a public face.\
\
If the law was being bent to protect allies, it was also being used to intimidate critics. The Department of Justice sent a formal letter to Representative Garcia accusing him of threatening Musk after critical comments, and Operation Whirlwind cast sharp political speech as a potential security issue. The U.S. Marshals Service was ordered to deputize members of Musk\'92s private security detail, allowing them to carry weapons on federal property. This move gave a billionaire\'92s guards a quasi-official status, blurring the line between public force and private protection. In immigration enforcement, ICE was authorized to detain people at courthouses and mandatory check-ins, including some with DACA protections, turning spaces of legal compliance into traps. These actions did not yet amount to open repression, but they made dissent and vulnerability more costly. They also signaled that the machinery of the state could be turned toward the defense of particular individuals and projects, not just the public at large. That signal was heard.\
