Symbolic control extended beyond curricula and websites. The administration asserted the power to rename Denali and the Gulf of Mexico by executive order, and Trump signed a proclamation declaring February 9 \'93Gulf of America Day\'94 while flying over the water he now insisted be called the Gulf of America. The Associated Press refused to adopt the new term in its stylebook and was punished for it. AP reporters were banned from the White House briefing room, the Oval Office, and Air Force One. The State Department ordered its embassies and consulates to cancel \'93non-mission critical\'94 media subscriptions, cutting off many diplomats from independent news sources. At the Kennedy Center, Trump installed himself as chair and replaced the board with loyalists, appointing Ric Grenell, a political ally without arts administration experience, as president. These moves did not yet erase all independent voices, but they shifted the center of gravity. Cultural institutions, press access, and even geographic names were being pulled into a single narrative project that glorified the leader, punished dissent, and erased histories that did not fit.\
\
Information control also took subtler forms. The Department of Government Efficiency claimed to have canceled $16 billion in wasteful contracts, but reporting showed that one supposed $8 billion cut was actually closer to $8 million. Congressman Nick Begich repeated false claims that millions of people over 100 years old were receiving Social Security benefits, echoing a debunked assertion from Musk. The administration froze funding for research that used the word \'93climate\'94 and removed climate change references from government websites, even as it declared an \'93energy emergency\'94 to fast-track hundreds of fossil fuel projects. Robert F. Kennedy Jr., newly installed as HHS Secretary, used a public appearance during Texas\'92s worst measles outbreak in decades to question the childhood vaccine schedule and suggest links between vaccines and chronic illness, despite scientific consensus to the contrary. Each of these actions chipped away at the public\'92s ability to rely on official numbers, scientific guidance, and basic facts. Together they created a fog in which drastic policy shifts could be justified by stories of fraud, waste, or hidden harms that did not withstand scrutiny.\
