Foreign policy, too, moved further from long-standing democratic alignments. In speeches and social media posts, Trump blamed Ukraine for the war with Russia, called President Zelensky a dictator, and demanded that Ukraine hold elections despite martial law and ongoing invasion. He spoke with Vladimir Putin for over an hour and described the call as \'93highly productive,\'94 echoing Russian rationales for the invasion. The administration sent a delegation to Saudi Arabia for peace talks with Russia that excluded Ukraine and its European allies, and in those talks Trump reportedly conceded to a list of Russian demands without securing reciprocal concessions. At the same time, Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent and other officials offered Ukraine support in exchange for half of its mineral resources, and the White House national security adviser pressed Kyiv to accept a $500 billion deal transferring half its mineral wealth to the United States. These proposals treated a besieged democracy\'92s natural resources as bargaining chips for American gain. They also signaled to allies that U.S. commitments could be converted into transactional deals, with sovereignty and justice subordinated to profit and personal diplomacy.\
