The administration\'92s posture toward Europe and NATO reflected the same shift. Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth told counterparts that the United States would not prioritize European security and that supporting Ukraine\'92s NATO membership or pre-2014 borders was unrealistic. Vice President J.D. Vance used the Munich Security Conference to attack European values and praise a far-right German party, breaking protocol by meeting its leader instead of the German chancellor. The U.S. prepared to withdraw troops from the Baltic states and explored a \'93deal\'94 with China to halve military spending on both sides, despite the opaque nature of Chinese defense budgets. In Riyadh, Secretary of State Marco Rubio agreed with Russia to restaff embassies, a key Russian demand to end its diplomatic isolation. These moves did not yet pull the United States out of NATO, a step Congress had preemptively constrained by law, and the European Union responded by approving new sanctions on Russia. But the direction of travel was clear. The administration was aligning its rhetoric and some of its actions with authoritarian powers, while treating democratic allies as obstacles or assets to be managed.\
