There were, amid these shifts, pockets of resistance and continuity. Federal courts twice refused to reinstate Trump\'92s ban on birthright citizenship, leaving in place injunctions that upheld the 14th Amendment\'92s guarantee. A judge blocked the firing of diversity staffers at the CIA and Office of the Director of National Intelligence, at least temporarily. Vermont and New York passed climate superfund laws to make fossil fuel companies pay for climate damages, even as red states and oil groups sued to stop them. The Federal Election Commission scheduled a Sunshine Act meeting on enforcement matters, and the National Archives announced a FOIA advisory committee session with public participation. The FCC finalized rules to make closed captioning settings more accessible, and routine regulatory notices continued to appear in the Federal Register. These actions did not reverse the week\'92s broader pattern, but they showed that not every institution had been captured, and not every lever of accountability had been removed. Some habits of rule-of-law governance persisted.\
\
Looking ahead from Week 5, several processes already in motion carried clear implications. The Supreme Court appeal over the firing of Hampton Dellinger, head of the Office of Special Counsel, would test whether whistleblower protections could survive a presidency that viewed independent oversight as an affront. Lawsuits over DOGE\'92s access to IRS and Social Security data, and over the legality of mass federal firings, would determine how far courts were willing to let a quasi-private network reshape the state. The climate superfund cases would decide whether states could hold fossil fuel companies financially responsible when the federal government would not. Internationally, the mineral rights proposals to Ukraine and the exclusion of Kyiv from peace talks in Saudi Arabia would either be ratified or rejected, with consequences for both sovereignty and the precedent of using aid as a lever for resource extraction. And at home, the open talk of a third presidential term, amplified by Steve Bannon\'92s call for a constitutional change, would either remain a fringe project or gather institutional support. The answers would set the terms of the next phase.\
