By the close of Week 5, with the Democracy Clock at 7:43 p.m., the story of Trump\'92s second term had entered a new phase. The early weeks had shown a willingness to test norms and stretch legal tools. This week showed a coordinated effort to make those tests permanent: to centralize control over regulators, to purge and privatize the civil service, to bend law enforcement toward friends and against critics, and to curate public memory so that alternative stories and histories faded from view. The clock\'92s movement captured not a single dramatic break, but the tightening of many smaller screws. It marked a moment when the distance between formal democracy and personal rule narrowed, not because elections had been canceled, but because the institutions that give elections meaning were being quietly stripped of their power. The time, 7:43 p.m., still left daylight on the dial. But the direction of travel, and the speed of the week, made clear how quickly that light could fade if these patterns held.\
